content: Write a comedic script for a play about two rival families running competing lemonade stands in their neighborhood.

**Title: Lemonade Wars**

**Characters:**

- **MRS. APPLETON** - The matriarch of the Appleton family, known for her traditional lemonade recipe.

- **MRS. BERRY** - The head of the Berry family, who believes in modernizing the classic lemonade.

- **TIMMY APPLETON** - Mrs. Appleton's son, a high school student with a knack for marketing.

- **SARAH BERRY** - Mrs. Berry's daughter, a college student with a passion for entrepreneurship.

- **NEIGHBOR TOM** - A friendly neighborhood guy who can't resist a good lemonade.

- **MS. JONES** - The local librarian with a sweet tooth.

**Setting:** A suburban neighborhood where the Appleton and Berry families have set up rival lemonade stands across the street from each other.

**Act 1, Scene 1**

*(The stage is divided into two sides, each with a lemonade stand. MRS. APPLETON is on one side, MRS. BERRY on the other. They are both setting up their stands as NEIGHBOR TOM walks by.)*

**NEIGHBOR TOM:** Oh, look at this! Two lemonade stands right across from each other? This is going to be interesting.

**MRS. APPLETON:** (Smiling) Welcome, Neighbor Tom! Trying to decide which lemonade to try first?

**MRS. BERRY:** (Confidently) I suggest you try mine first. Our lemonade is infused with exotic berries and has a touch of mint.

**MRS. APPLETON:** (Sniffing) Exotic berries, hmm? My traditional recipe has been passed down for generations. Real lemons, real sugar, real flavor.

**NEIGHBOR TOM:** (Laughing) Well, I might just need to try both to make a decision.

*(He walks over to MRS. APPLETON's stand.)*

**MRS. APPLETON:** Here you go, Neighbor Tom. A fresh cup of Appleton's finest.

*(He takes a sip.)*

**NEIGHBOR TOM:** Mmm, delicious! Very refreshing.

*(He walks over to MRS. BERRY's stand.)*

**MRS. BERRY:** Try some of ours. You won't be disappointed.

*(He takes a sip.)*

**NEIGHBOR TOM:** Wow, this is different. I like the berry flavor. It's got a nice kick.

**MRS. APPLETON:** (Skeptical) Kick? Lemonade should be straightforward, not all fancy.

**MRS. BERRY:** (Defensive) Times are changing, Mrs. Appleton. People want something new and exciting.

**MRS. APPLETON:** Well, I'll stick to what works. Now, if you'll excuse me, I have to make sure my lemonade is just right.

*(She walks back to her stand and starts adjusting something.)*

**Act 1, Scene 2**

*(TIMMY APPLETON and SARAH BERRY enter from opposite sides. They see each other and groan.)*

**TIMMY APPLETON:** Great, she's here too.

**SARAH BERRY:** (Smirking) Looks like the competition is heating up.

**TIMMY APPLETON:** You think? Mom's already at it with your mom.

**SARAH BERRY:** Yeah, well, maybe if your mom would try something new, she wouldn't be so threatened.

**TIMMY APPLETON:** Threatened? Mom doesn't get threatened by anyone, especially not by some fancy-pants lemonade.

**SARAH BERRY:** Oh, please. My lemonade is not fancy-pants. It's innovative.

**TIMMY APPLETON:** Innovative my foot. It's just lemonade with berries and mint. Anyone can do that.

**SARAH BERRY:** Anyone can make lemonade, but not everyone can make it stand out.

**TIMMY APPLETON:** Well, we'll see about that. I've got some marketing tricks up my sleeve.

**SARAH BERRY:** Oh really? Like what?

**TIMMY APPLETON:** Surprise! You'll see.

*(They both walk to their respective stands, muttering to themselves.)*

**Act 2, Scene 1**

*(MS. JONES walks by, looking at both stands hesitantly.)*

**MS. JONES:** Oh dear, both stands look so inviting. I can't decide which one to choose.

**MRS. APPLETON:** Come over here, Ms. Jones! Try our classic lemonade. It's the taste of summer.

**MRS. BERRY:** Or come try ours! We have a special blend with strawberries and basil. It's a real treat.

**MS. JONES:** (To MRS. APPLETON) But your recipe is so traditional and comforting.

**MS. BERRY:** And ours is a refreshing twist on the classic.

**MS. JONES:** (Sighs) Maybe I should try both.

*(She walks over to MRS. APPLETON's stand and takes a sip.)*

**MS. JONES:** Mmm, yes, just like I remember.

*(Then she walks over to MRS. BERRY's stand and takes a sip.)*

**MS. JONES:** Oh, this is delightful! The strawberries really bring out the flavor.

**MRS. APPLETON:** (Frowning) Well, I think sometimes classic is better.

**MRS. BERRY:** And sometimes, a little innovation can make all the difference.

**MS. JONES:** Maybe a mix of both would be perfect.

*(She walks away, still pondering.)*

**Act 2, Scene 2**

*(TIMMY APPLETON is handing out flyers around the neighborhood. SARAH BERRY is setting up a sign that says "New Flavor: Lemonade with a Kick!" TIMMY APPLETON notices and walks over.)*

**TIMMY APPLETON:** What's this? Lemonade with a kick? Sounds suspicious.

**SARAH BERRY:** (Laughs) No, not that kind of kick. It's just a zesty twist.

**TIMMY APPLETON:** Well, we've got our own twist. Check out these flyers. "Appleton's Awesome Lemonade: The Original Refreshment."

**SARAH BERRY:** (Reading the flyer) "Awesome Lemonade"? Really?

**TIMMY APPLETON:** Why not? It's catchy.

**SARAH BERRY:** Catchy, maybe, but ours has actual unique selling points.

**TIMMY APPLETON:** Like what?

**SARAH BERRY:** Like our use of fresh berries and herbs. It's healthier and more flavorful.

**TIMMY APPLETON:** Healthier? Since when did lemonade need to be healthy?

**SARAH BERRY:** Because people are health-conscious these days. They want something sweet without feeling guilty.

**TIMMY APPLETON:** Well, maybe our lemonade is just pure, unadulterated sweetness.

**SARAH BERRY:** Adulterated? Your lemonade is fine, but it's not evolving.

**TIMMY APPLETON:** Evolving? Lemonade doesn't need to evolve. It's perfect the way it is.

**SARAH BERRY:** Obviously, you haven't tried ours yet.

**TIMMY APPLETON:** (Snorts) I don't need to. I know good lemonade when I taste it.

**SARAH BERRY:** Suit yourself.

*(They both return to their stands, continuing to promote their lemonade in their own ways.)*

**Act 3, Scene 1**

*(The neighborhood kids are gathered around both stands, trying to decide where to buy their lemonade.)*

**KID 1:** I heard that Berry's has strawberry lemonade.

**KID 2:** But Appleton's is the original. Maybe I should stick with that.

**KID 3:** Maybe we can split and try both.

*(They decide to buy from both stands and compare.)*

**MRS. APPLETON:** (To the kids) Special deal today! Buy one get one free.
